[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":801},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F25\u002Fvar-vs-let-and-undeclared-variables\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F25\u002Fvar-vs-let-and-undeclared-variables\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F25\u002Fvar-vs-let-and-undeclared-variables\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F25\u002Fvar-vs-let-and-undeclared-variables\u002F":776,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F25\u002Fvar-vs-let-and-undeclared-variables\u002F":785},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200425\u002F539985371\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":760,"date":761,"description":762,"extension":763,"lang":764,"meta":765,"navigation":131,"path":766,"readingMinutes":767,"seo":768,"standalone":769,"stem":770,"tags":771,"tldr":773,"updated":761,"url":774,"__hash__":775},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fvar-vs-let-and-undeclared-variables.md","var vs let in JavaScript — Plus What Happens When You Forget to Declare a Variable","1001560046",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":753},"minimark",[11,16,29,33,39,49,58,68,83,157,171,180,184,206,216,273,279,293,343,346,446,452,542,555,562,571,574,578,585,613,618,627,652,658,665,671,691,694,697,705,708,726,730,749],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19,20,24,25,28],"p",{},"Plenty of people online have already covered the difference between ",[21,22,23],"code",{},"var"," and ",[21,26,27],{},"let",", and what happens when you forget to declare a variable at all. So here's my take — the biggest differences between these two, plus the gotcha with skipping the declaration keyword.",[12,30,32],{"id":31},"what-happens-when-you-skip-the-declaration-keyword","What happens when you skip the declaration keyword",[17,34,35,36,38],{},"Honestly the heading should be \"the difference between using ",[21,37,23],{}," and not using it\", but in plain English we tend to say \"declaring a variable or not\". Before I get into it though, you need to know two concepts:",[40,41,42,46],"ul",{},[43,44,45],"li",{},"The global environment",[43,47,48],{},"The global object",[17,50,51,52,57],{},"I already covered both of these in ",[53,54,56],"a",{"href":55},"\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F20190515\u002F1050733096\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.3 Global Environment and Global Object (article in Mandarin)",", so I won't repeat them here. Let me jump straight to the point.",[17,59,60,61,63,64,67],{},"In normal situations, the biggest difference between using ",[21,62,23],{}," and not using it comes down to one thing: \"can it be deleted with ",[21,65,66],{},"delete","?\"",[17,69,70,72,73,79,80,82],{},[21,71,66],{}," is the syntax for removing a property from an object — there's a write-up on ",[53,74,78],{"href":75,"rel":76},"https:\u002F\u002Fdeveloper.mozilla.org\u002Fen-US\u002Fdocs\u002FWeb\u002FJavaScript\u002FReference\u002FOperators\u002Fdelete",[77],"nofollow","MDN",". So we can use the snippet below to see the difference between declaring with ",[21,81,23],{}," and not:",[84,85,90],"pre",{"className":86,"code":87,"language":88,"meta":89,"style":89},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var a = 'a';\ndelete a; \u002F\u002F false\n\nb = 'b';\ndelete b; \u002F\u002F true\n","js","",[21,91,92,114,126,133,146],{"__ignoreMap":89},[93,94,97,100,104,107,111],"span",{"class":95,"line":96},"line",1,[93,98,23],{"class":99},"sWyjQ",[93,101,103],{"class":102},"sMAXC"," a ",[93,105,106],{"class":99},"=",[93,108,110],{"class":109},"sTRMh"," 'a'",[93,112,113],{"class":102},";\n",[93,115,117,119,122],{"class":95,"line":116},2,[93,118,66],{"class":99},[93,120,121],{"class":102}," a; ",[93,123,125],{"class":124},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F false\n",[93,127,129],{"class":95,"line":128},3,[93,130,132],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":131},true,"\n",[93,134,136,139,141,144],{"class":95,"line":135},4,[93,137,138],{"class":102},"b ",[93,140,106],{"class":99},[93,142,143],{"class":109}," 'b'",[93,145,113],{"class":102},[93,147,149,151,154],{"class":95,"line":148},5,[93,150,66],{"class":99},[93,152,153],{"class":102}," b; ",[93,155,156],{"class":124},"\u002F\u002F true\n",[17,158,159,160,162,163,167,168,170],{},"That tells us something important: a variable created without ",[21,161,23],{}," gets added ",[164,165,166],"strong",{},"as an object property",". So I'd strongly recommend you always declare variables with ",[21,169,23],{}," — a variable that can be deleted is an easy way to introduce system bugs.",[17,172,173,174,24,176,179],{},"I'm leaving ",[21,175,27],{},[21,177,178],{},"const"," out of this part for now.",[12,181,183],{"id":182},"scope","Scope",[17,185,186,187,189,190,24,192,194,195,197,198,200,201,24,203,205],{},"Next let's look at the scope of ",[21,188,23],{}," versus ",[21,191,27],{},[21,193,178],{},". Generally the advice is to swap all your old ",[21,196,23],{}," declarations over to ",[21,199,27],{}," — but what's the actual difference between ",[21,202,27],{},[21,204,23],{},"?",[17,207,208,209,211,212,215],{},"Start with ",[21,210,23],{},". Its scope is ",[164,213,214],{},"function scope",", which means the variable's scope is decided by the function it lives in. For example:",[84,217,219],{"className":86,"code":218,"language":88,"meta":89,"style":89},"function fuA() {\n  var a = 'a';\n}\nfuA();\nconsole.log(a); \u002F\u002F a is not defined\n",[21,220,221,233,246,251,259],{"__ignoreMap":89},[93,222,223,226,230],{"class":95,"line":96},[93,224,225],{"class":99},"function",[93,227,229],{"class":228},"sj_SG"," fuA",[93,231,232],{"class":102},"() {\n",[93,234,235,238,240,242,244],{"class":95,"line":116},[93,236,237],{"class":99},"  var",[93,239,103],{"class":102},[93,241,106],{"class":99},[93,243,110],{"class":109},[93,245,113],{"class":102},[93,247,248],{"class":95,"line":128},[93,249,250],{"class":102},"}\n",[93,252,253,256],{"class":95,"line":135},[93,254,255],{"class":228},"fuA",[93,257,258],{"class":102},"();\n",[93,260,261,264,267,270],{"class":95,"line":148},[93,262,263],{"class":102},"console.",[93,265,266],{"class":228},"log",[93,268,269],{"class":102},"(a); ",[93,271,272],{"class":124},"\u002F\u002F a is not defined\n",[17,274,275,276,278],{},"We can't reach the variable declared inside ",[21,277,255],{},", even though we've already called and run it.",[17,280,281,282,284,285,288,289,292],{},"What about ",[21,283,27],{},"? Its scope is ",[164,286,287],{},"block scope",". The easiest way to spot it: anywhere there's a pair of ",[21,290,291],{},"{ }"," curly braces, that's its scope.",[84,294,296],{"className":86,"code":295,"language":88,"meta":89,"style":89},"if(true) {\n  let a = 'a';\n}\n\nconsole.log(a);\n",[21,297,298,313,326,330,334],{"__ignoreMap":89},[93,299,300,303,306,310],{"class":95,"line":96},[93,301,302],{"class":99},"if",[93,304,305],{"class":102},"(",[93,307,309],{"class":308},"sCcAr","true",[93,311,312],{"class":102},") {\n",[93,314,315,318,320,322,324],{"class":95,"line":116},[93,316,317],{"class":99},"  let",[93,319,103],{"class":102},[93,321,106],{"class":99},[93,323,110],{"class":109},[93,325,113],{"class":102},[93,327,328],{"class":95,"line":128},[93,329,250],{"class":102},[93,331,332],{"class":95,"line":135},[93,333,132],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":131},[93,335,336,338,340],{"class":95,"line":148},[93,337,263],{"class":102},[93,339,266],{"class":228},[93,341,342],{"class":102},"(a);\n",[17,344,345],{},"If you try to compare the two using functions, you won't see the difference, because the scopes look the same.",[84,347,349],{"className":86,"code":348,"language":88,"meta":89,"style":89},"function fuA() {\n  var a = 'a';\n}\nfuA();\nconsole.log(a); \u002F\u002F a is not defined\n\nfunction fuB() {\n  let b = 'b';\n}\nfuB();\nconsole.log(b); \u002F\u002F b is not defined\n",[21,350,351,359,371,375,381,391,396,406,420,425,433],{"__ignoreMap":89},[93,352,353,355,357],{"class":95,"line":96},[93,354,225],{"class":99},[93,356,229],{"class":228},[93,358,232],{"class":102},[93,360,361,363,365,367,369],{"class":95,"line":116},[93,362,237],{"class":99},[93,364,103],{"class":102},[93,366,106],{"class":99},[93,368,110],{"class":109},[93,370,113],{"class":102},[93,372,373],{"class":95,"line":128},[93,374,250],{"class":102},[93,376,377,379],{"class":95,"line":135},[93,378,255],{"class":228},[93,380,258],{"class":102},[93,382,383,385,387,389],{"class":95,"line":148},[93,384,263],{"class":102},[93,386,266],{"class":228},[93,388,269],{"class":102},[93,390,272],{"class":124},[93,392,394],{"class":95,"line":393},6,[93,395,132],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":131},[93,397,399,401,404],{"class":95,"line":398},7,[93,400,225],{"class":99},[93,402,403],{"class":228}," fuB",[93,405,232],{"class":102},[93,407,409,411,414,416,418],{"class":95,"line":408},8,[93,410,317],{"class":99},[93,412,413],{"class":102}," b ",[93,415,106],{"class":99},[93,417,143],{"class":109},[93,419,113],{"class":102},[93,421,423],{"class":95,"line":422},9,[93,424,250],{"class":102},[93,426,428,431],{"class":95,"line":427},10,[93,429,430],{"class":228},"fuB",[93,432,258],{"class":102},[93,434,436,438,440,443],{"class":95,"line":435},11,[93,437,263],{"class":102},[93,439,266],{"class":228},[93,441,442],{"class":102},"(b); ",[93,444,445],{"class":124},"\u002F\u002F b is not defined\n",[17,447,448,449,451],{},"But once you use something like an ",[21,450,302],{}," block, the difference shows up:",[84,453,455],{"className":86,"code":454,"language":88,"meta":89,"style":89},"if(true) {\n  var a = 'a';\n}\n\nconsole.log(a); \u002F\u002F a\n\nif(true) {\n  let b = 'b';\n}\n\nconsole.log(b); \u002F\u002F b is not defined\n",[21,456,457,467,479,483,487,498,502,512,524,528,532],{"__ignoreMap":89},[93,458,459,461,463,465],{"class":95,"line":96},[93,460,302],{"class":99},[93,462,305],{"class":102},[93,464,309],{"class":308},[93,466,312],{"class":102},[93,468,469,471,473,475,477],{"class":95,"line":116},[93,470,237],{"class":99},[93,472,103],{"class":102},[93,474,106],{"class":99},[93,476,110],{"class":109},[93,478,113],{"class":102},[93,480,481],{"class":95,"line":128},[93,482,250],{"class":102},[93,484,485],{"class":95,"line":135},[93,486,132],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":131},[93,488,489,491,493,495],{"class":95,"line":148},[93,490,263],{"class":102},[93,492,266],{"class":228},[93,494,269],{"class":102},[93,496,497],{"class":124},"\u002F\u002F a\n",[93,499,500],{"class":95,"line":393},[93,501,132],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":131},[93,503,504,506,508,510],{"class":95,"line":398},[93,505,302],{"class":99},[93,507,305],{"class":102},[93,509,309],{"class":308},[93,511,312],{"class":102},[93,513,514,516,518,520,522],{"class":95,"line":408},[93,515,317],{"class":99},[93,517,413],{"class":102},[93,519,106],{"class":99},[93,521,143],{"class":109},[93,523,113],{"class":102},[93,525,526],{"class":95,"line":422},[93,527,250],{"class":102},[93,529,530],{"class":95,"line":427},[93,531,132],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":131},[93,533,534,536,538,540],{"class":95,"line":435},[93,535,263],{"class":102},[93,537,266],{"class":228},[93,539,442],{"class":102},[93,541,445],{"class":124},[17,543,544,545,547,548,551,552,554],{},"So the upside of declaring with ",[21,546,27],{}," is that we can be sure we won't pollute the global object — because any variable that isn't declared ",[164,549,550],{},"inside a function"," ends up polluting the global object. The ",[21,553,302],{}," example above pollutes it:",[17,556,557],{},[558,559],"img",{"alt":560,"src":561},"Polluting the global object with var","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-04-26%2020.59.23.png",[17,563,564,565,567,568,570],{},"You might ask: \"What about ",[21,566,178],{},"?\" Same as ",[21,569,27],{},", basically.",[17,572,573],{},"I'm not going to get into Hoisting here — maybe another time.",[12,575,577],{"id":576},"why-you-cant-find-a-let-variable-on-window","Why you can't find a let variable on window",[17,579,580,581,584],{},"This is something almost nobody mentions. Back in the day, after declaring a variable like this, you could always find it under ",[21,582,583],{},"window",":",[84,586,588],{"className":86,"code":587,"language":88,"meta":89,"style":89},"var aName = 'Ray';\nconsole.log(window);\n",[21,589,590,604],{"__ignoreMap":89},[93,591,592,594,597,599,602],{"class":95,"line":96},[93,593,23],{"class":99},[93,595,596],{"class":102}," aName ",[93,598,106],{"class":99},[93,600,601],{"class":109}," 'Ray'",[93,603,113],{"class":102},[93,605,606,608,610],{"class":95,"line":116},[93,607,263],{"class":102},[93,609,266],{"class":228},[93,611,612],{"class":102},"(window);\n",[17,614,615],{},[558,616],{"alt":583,"src":617},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-04-26%2021.03.31.png",[17,619,620,621,623,624,626],{},"But once we use ES6 syntax — ",[21,622,27],{}," or ",[21,625,178],{}," — that variable is nowhere to be found:",[84,628,630],{"className":86,"code":629,"language":88,"meta":89,"style":89},"let aName = 'Ray';\nconsole.log(window);\n",[21,631,632,644],{"__ignoreMap":89},[93,633,634,636,638,640,642],{"class":95,"line":96},[93,635,27],{"class":99},[93,637,596],{"class":102},[93,639,106],{"class":99},[93,641,601],{"class":109},[93,643,113],{"class":102},[93,645,646,648,650],{"class":95,"line":116},[93,647,263],{"class":102},[93,649,266],{"class":228},[93,651,612],{"class":102},[17,653,654],{},[558,655],{"alt":656,"src":657},"Can't find the variable declared with let","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-04-26%2021.05.11.png",[17,659,660,661,664],{},"And yet, if we reference ",[21,662,663],{},"aName"," directly, we still get the declared variable back just fine:",[17,666,667],{},[558,668],{"alt":669,"src":670},"Not on window but still retrievable","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-04-26%2021.06.27.png",[17,672,673,674,676,677,679,680,682,683,686,687,690],{},"So what's the deal? In our usual mental model, declared variables get added to ",[21,675,583],{},". But a variable declared with ",[21,678,27],{}," can't be found under ",[21,681,583],{}," — even though you can still call it and get the right value. And if you try ",[21,684,685],{},"delete aName",", you'll also get a ",[21,688,689],{},"false",", meaning it can't be deleted.",[17,692,693],{},"Is it magic? Nope.",[17,695,696],{},"The reason lies in the global space. The global space is actually made up of two environments:",[40,698,699,702],{},[43,700,701],{},"The global object — Object Env",[43,703,704],{},"The declarative environment — Declare Env",[17,706,707],{},"So the global space is really a two-environment thing, and normally we never see the Declare Env.",[17,709,710,712,713,24,715,717,718,623,720,722,723,725],{},[21,711,23],{}," is declared based on the Object Env and added to the Declare Env, while ",[21,714,27],{},[21,716,178],{}," are only declared in the Declare Env. That's exactly why we can't see variables declared with ",[21,719,27],{},[21,721,178],{}," on ",[21,724,583],{},", but can still get their values just fine.",[12,727,729],{"id":728},"references","References",[40,731,732,742],{},[43,733,734],{},[53,735,738,739],{"href":736,"rel":737},"https:\u002F\u002Fstackoverflow.com\u002Fquestions\u002F39414692\u002Fa-javascript-let-global-variable-is-not-a-property-of-window-unlike-a-global",[77],"A javascript 'let' global variable is not a property of 'window' unlike a global 'var' ",[93,740,741],{},"duplicate",[43,743,744],{},[53,745,748],{"href":746,"rel":747},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002FAdvanced-Frontend\u002FDaily-Interview-Question\u002Fissues\u002F30",[77],"第 27 题：关于 const 和 let 声明的变量不在 window 上",[750,751,752],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html pre.shiki code .sQrFR, html code.shiki .sQrFR{--shiki-default:#BDC4CC}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}",{"title":89,"searchDepth":116,"depth":116,"links":754},[755,756,757,758,759],{"id":14,"depth":116,"text":15},{"id":31,"depth":116,"text":32},{"id":182,"depth":116,"text":183},{"id":576,"depth":116,"text":577},{"id":728,"depth":116,"text":729},"JavaScript","2020-04-25 17:50:27","Plenty of people online have covered the difference between var and let, and what happens when you skip the declaration keyword entirely. So here's my take on it too — the biggest differences between var and let, why forgetting the keyword bites you, and the one weird thing almost nobody mentions: why a let variable can't be found on window but still works.","md","en",{},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002Fvar-vs-let-and-undeclared-variables","4",{"title":6,"description":762},false,"en\u002FJavaScript\u002Fvar-vs-let-and-undeclared-variables",[772,760],"ES6",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F25\u002Fvar-vs-let-and-undeclared-variables\u002F","aGEfcsuhkH2yXm8wqfz4EfDdYHvdK_wuBXjHN2fMc7A",{"newer":777,"older":781},{"url":778,"title":779,"date":780},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F27\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-12-mousemove-event-2\u002F","PixiJS V5 Tutorial (12) - mousemoveEvent (2)","2020-04-27 08:59:26",{"url":782,"title":783,"date":784},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F20\u002Fpixijs-v5-11-mousemove\u002F","PixiJS V5 Tutorial (11) - Making a Sprite Follow Your Mouse","2020-04-20 08:35:59",[786,791,796],{"url":787,"title":788,"date":789,"readingMinutes":790},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2026\u002F03\u002F10\u002Fweb-crypto-api-encryption-guide\u002F","No crypto Package, No Node.js — The Web Crypto API Does It All in the Browser","2026-03-10 09:45:08","9",{"url":792,"title":793,"date":794,"readingMinutes":795},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F08\u002Fjquery-why-it-declined\u002F","jQuery Was Once King — So Why Did It Fall Off?","2025-12-08 21:35:24","7",{"url":797,"title":798,"date":799,"readingMinutes":800},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F05\u002Fjavascript-generator-functions\u002F","What Are JavaScript Generator Functions (function*)? The Function You Can Pause and Resume","2025-12-05 13:40:31","5",1784013060712]